MOSS-TTS-Nano Voice Prompts
============================

This directory contains .wav prompt audio files used by MOSS-TTS-Nano
for voice cloning. Each .wav file defines a "voice" — the TTS engine
clones the speaker's voice from the prompt audio and generates new
speech in that voice.

How it works:
- Each .wav file in this directory is a voice.
- The voice name is the filename without .wav (e.g. en_warm_female.wav → "en_warm_female").
- The .wav file should be 5-30 seconds of clean speech from the speaker you want to clone.
- Use ?djvoices in Discord to see available voices.

Adding custom voices:
1. Record or obtain a clean speech sample (5-30 seconds, no background music/noise)
2. Save it as a .wav file in this directory (e.g. my_voice.wav)
3. Set DJ_VOICE=my_voice in your .env (or use ?djvoice my_voice in Discord)
4. The bot will use this as the prompt audio for voice cloning

Naming convention:
- Use language prefix: en_, zh_, ja_, ko_, de_, es_, fr_, etc.
- Then voice description: en_warm_female, en_news_male, zh_gentle_female
- Keep filenames lowercase with underscores

Available voices:
- en_warm_female: Default DJ voice (warm, friendly female English voice)
- en_news_male: News anchor style male English voice (good for AI side host)